problem: If the two roots of the quadratic $3x^2+5x+k$ are $\frac{-5\pm i\sqrt{11}}{6}$, what is $k$?
model_solution:
Step 1:  Use the quadratic formula to find the relationship between the coefficients of the quadratic equation and the roots.
\[x=\frac{-b\pm \sqrt{b^{2}-4ac}}{2a}\]
\[3x^{2}+5x+k=0\]
\[a=3,\ \ b=5,\ \ c=k\]
\[x=\frac{-5\pm \sqrt{5^{2}-4(3)(k)}}{2(3)}\]
\[\frac{-5\pm \sqrt{25-12k}}{6}\]
Step 2:  Given that $\frac{-5\pm i\sqrt{11}}{6}$, we have $\frac{-5\pm i\sqrt{11}}{6}=\frac{-5\pm \sqrt{25-12k}}{6}$.
$\sqrt{25-12k}=i\sqrt{11}$
$25-12k=-11$
$-12k=-11-25$
$-12k=-36$
$k=3$
Since $\sqrt{25-12k}=-i\sqrt{11}$ is not possible,
$\sqrt{25-12k}=i\sqrt{11}$
$25-12k=-11$
$-12k=-11-25$
$-12k=-36$
$k=3$
Since $\sqrt{25-12k}=i\sqrt{11}$ is not possible,
$25-12k=11$
$-12k=11-25$
$-12k=-14$
$k=\frac{-14}{-12}$
$k=\frac{7}{6}$
Since $\sqrt{25-12k}=i\sqrt{11}$ is not possible,
$25-12k=11$
$-12k=11-25$
$-12k=-14$
$k=\frac{-14}{-12}$
$k=\frac{7}{6}$
